## 5. What Judges Actually Score

### Universal Judging Rubric (Synthesized from 20+ hackathons)

| Criteria | Weight | What Gets a 5/5 | What Gets a 1/5 |
|----------|--------|-----------------|-----------------|
| **Technical Execution** | 25% | Working demo, clean code, uses APIs creatively | Slide deck only, broken demo, copy-paste code |
| **Innovation** | 25% | Never-seen-before approach, creative tech combination | Generic CRUD app, tutorial-level project |
| **Problem Relevance** | 20% | Clear pain point, real user evidence, data-backed | Vague problem, no real users identified |
| **Design/UX** | 15% | Polished UI, intuitive flow, responsive | Default Bootstrap, confusing navigation |
| **Presentation** | 15% | Compelling story, confident demo, clear roadmap | Reads slides, mumbles, no roadmap |

> [!WARNING]
> **#1 Killer:** Not having a working demo. A mediocre working app ALWAYS beats a brilliant broken one.

### Secret Judging Biases (What Nobody Tells You)

1. **The "First 30 Seconds" Rule** — Judges form 70% of their opinion in the first 30 seconds of your demo
2. **Sponsor Tech Bonus** — Using the hackathon sponsor's API/tools often gets you extra consideration
3. **The "So What?" Test** — After every demo, judges internally ask "Would anyone actually use this?"
4. **Team Energy** — Enthusiastic teams with clear role division always leave a better impression
5. **Edge Cases** — Mentioning how you handle edge cases (even if not built) shows maturity

